08245nam a22009615i 9780271060293DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212012pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710602937 a10.1515/97802710602932doi  a(DE-B1597)584562  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aJF801b.R52 2012eb 7aLAN0040002bisacsh04a323.601/422300aRhetorical Citizenship and Public Deliberation /ced. by Lisa Villadsen, Christian Kock. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b1 illustration  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRhetoric and Democratic Deliberation ;v300tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: citizenship as a rhetorical practice -- tSection I: Tracing rhetorical citizenship as concept and practice -- t1 Deliberative Democracy: Mapping Out the Deliberative Turn in Democratic Theory -- t2 The Making of Truth in Debate: The Case of (and a Case for) the Early Sophists -- t3 The Search for "Real" Democracy: Rhetorical Citizenship and Public Deliberation in France and the United States, 1870-1940 -- tSection II: Public deliberation as rhetorical practice -- tIntroduction -- tPart 1 Considering Norms of Communicative Behavior -- t4 The Respect Fallacy: Limits of Respect in Public Dialogue -- t5 Dialectical Citizenship? Some Thoughts on the Role of Pragmatics in the Analysis of Public Debate -- t6 Provocative Style: The Gaarder Debate Example -- t7 Virtual Deliberations: Talking Politics Online in Hungary -- tPart 2 Critiques of "Elite" Discourse -- t8 Dis-playing Democracy: The Rhetoric of Duplicity -- t9 Rhetoric of War, Rhetoric of Gender -- t10 Speaking of Terror: Norms of Rhetorical Citizenship in Danish Public Discourse -- t11 "This May Be the Law, but Should It Be?": Tony Blair's Rhetoric of Exception -- tPart 3 Rhetorical Citizenship Across Communicative Settings -- t12 I Agree, but . . . : Finding Alternatives to Controversial Projects Through Public Deliberation -- t13 Deliberation as Behavior in Public -- t14 Homing in on the Arguments: The Rhetorical Construction of Subject Positions in Debates on the Danish Real Estate Market -- t15 Danish Revue: Satire as Rhetorical Citizenship -- tSection III: Toward better deliberative practices -- t16 Presidential Primary Debate as a Genre of Journalistic Discourse: How Can We Put Debate into the Debates? -- t17 A Tool for Rhetorical Citizenship: Generalizing the Status System -- t18 Interpretive Debates Revisited -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCitizenship has long been a central topic among educators, philosophers, and political theorists. Using the phrase "rhetorical citizenship" as a unifying perspective, Rhetorical Citizenship and Public Deliberation aims to develop an understanding of citizenship as a discursive phenomenon, arguing that discourse is not prefatory to real action but in many ways constitutive of civic engagement. To accomplish this, the book brings together, in a cross-disciplinary effort, contributions by scholars in fields that rarely intersect. For the most part, discussions of citizenship have focused on aspects that are central to the "liberal" tradition of social thought-that is, questions of the freedoms and rights of citizens and groups. This collection gives voice to a "republican" conception of citizenship. Seeing participation and debate as central to being a citizen, this tradition looks back to the Greek city-states and republican Rome. Citizenship, in this sense of the word, is rhetorical citizenship. Rhetoric is thus at the core of being a citizen. Aside from the editors, the contributors are John Adams, Paula Cossart, Jonas Gabrielsen, Jette Barnholdt Hansen, Kasper Møller Hansen, Sine Nørholm Just, Ildikó Kaposi, William Keith, Bart van Klink, Marie Lund Klujeff, Manfred Kraus, Oliver W. Lembcke, Berit von der Lippe, James McDonald, Niels Møller Nielsen, Tatiana Tatarchevskiy, Italo Testa, Georgia Warnke, Kristian Wedberg, and Stephen West.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aCitizenship. 0aDeliberative democracy. 0aPolitical participation. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Communication Studies.2bisacsh1 aAdams, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarnholdt Hansen, Jette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCossart, Paula, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGabrielsen, Jonas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaposi, Ildikó, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeith, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlink, Bart van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKock, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKock, Christian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKraus, Manfred, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLembcke, Oliver W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLippe, Berit von der, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLund Klujeff, Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcDonald, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMøller Hansen, Kasper, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMøller Nielsen, Niels, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNørholm Just, Sine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTatarchevskiy, Tatiana, eco